Halve, peel, and finely chop the @yellow onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Core, seed, and remove the white veins from the @green bell pepper{1}(cored, seeded, and cut into thin strips). Cut into thin strips, then cube. Cut the @celery{1%stalk}(cut into 1/2-inch pieces). Thinly slice the @scallions{2}(thinly sliced).

Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a #pot{} over medium heat. Add the onion, celery, and half the green bell pepper. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. Cook for about ~{5%minutes}, until softened.

Add the @rice{3/4%cup}, @cumin{1%teaspoon}, @chili powder{1%teaspoon}, and @cayenne pepper{1%teaspoon}(pinch, careful, it's spicy!). Cook for about ~{1%minute}, stirring, to toast.

Add the @diced tomatoes{1%can}, @veggie stock concentrate{1%cube}, and @water{2%cups} and bring to a boil. Reduce to a simmer and cook for ~{15-20%minutes} or until rice is tender, stirring occasionally.

Season the @shrimp{10%ounce} with salt and pepper. Add the shrimp and remaining bell pepper to the rice and stir. Cook for about ~{3-5%minutes}, until shrimp are pink and opaque in the center.

Serve the jambalaya with a sprinkle of scallions on top!

> This dish kicks off with the Cajun "Holy Trinity": celery, onion, and bell pepper. Rice is cooked in a rich tomato sauce for the ultimate flavor bomb. We added juicy shrimp, but sausage or chicken would go equally well in this classic dish.